{
  "executive_summary": "The courier tracking system requires a hybrid storage architecture. Bird's hard domain rule — location readings older than 30 seconds must NEVER be displayed — creates a fundamental tension with the team's proposal to use PostgreSQL as the sole storage layer. PostgreSQL can store location data, but it lacks native TTL/expiry semantics needed to enforce the 30-second staleness invariant at the infrastructure level. Relying solely on application-layer staleness checks against PostgreSQL is fragile and violates defense-in-depth. The recommended architecture uses Redis for current/ephemeral location state (with native TTL enforcement) and PostgreSQL for historical location audit trails, connected via WebSocket/SSE push to customers.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Location Ingestion Service",
        "responsibility": "Receives GPS pings from courier devices via lightweight protocol (HTTP/2 or MQTT). Validates payload, timestamps, and courier identity. Publishes validated location events.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the write path only. Knows nothing about customer-facing reads. Stateless — scales horizontally."
      },
      {
        "name": "Current Location Store (Redis)",
        "responsibility": "Stores the LATEST known location per courier with a 30-second TTL. This is the ONLY read source for customer-facing location queries. When TTL expires, the key disappears — making it structurally impossible to serve stale data.",
        "boundaries": "Ephemeral data only. Not a system of record. Loses data on failure (acceptable — next ping restores it)."
      },
      {
        "name": "Location History Store (PostgreSQL)",
        "responsibility": "Append-only historical record of all courier location updates. Used for analytics, dispute resolution, route optimization, and audit. Never read by the customer-facing path for current location.",
        "boundaries": "System of record for historical data. Not queried for real-time display. Partitioned by time for efficient retention management."
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Push Gateway",
        "responsibility": "Maintains WebSocket/SSE connections to customers tracking active deliveries. Subscribes to Redis Pub/Sub for location updates. Pushes fresh locations to connected clients. If no update arrives within 30 seconds, pushes a 'location unavailable' event instead of serving stale data.",
        "boundaries": "Read path only. Owns the customer connection lifecycle. Enforces staleness at the delivery layer as a second line of defense."
      },
      {
        "name": "Staleness Enforcement Middleware",
        "responsibility": "Application-layer guard that validates timestamp freshness on ANY location read, regardless of source. Defense-in-depth — catches edge cases where Redis TTL alone might not suffice (clock skew, replication lag).",
        "boundaries": "Cross-cutting concern. Runs in the read path before any location data reaches a customer response."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Courier Device",
        "to": "Location Ingestion Service",
        "contract": "POST /locations { courier_id, lat, lng, timestamp, accuracy } — authenticated via device token, minimum ping interval 5s, maximum 15s",
        "coupling_type": "loose — protocol-based, versioned API"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Ingestion Service",
        "to": "Current Location Store (Redis)",
        "contract": "SET courier:{id}:location {payload} EX 30 — atomic write with TTL. Also PUBLISH to channel courier:{id}:updates",
        "coupling_type": "loose — Redis protocol, replaceable with any TTL-capable KV store"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Ingestion Service",
        "to": "Location History Store (PostgreSQL)",
        "contract": "INSERT INTO courier_locations (courier_id, lat, lng, accuracy, device_timestamp, received_at) — async via write buffer/queue, not in critical path",
        "coupling_type": "loose — async write, failure does not block ingestion"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Push Gateway",
        "to": "Current Location Store (Redis)",
        "contract": "SUBSCRIBE courier:{id}:updates for push; GET courier:{id}:location for initial load. Absence of key = location unavailable.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — Pub/Sub subscription, stateless reconnection"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Push Gateway",
        "to": "Customer Client",
        "contract": "WebSocket frame: { type: 'location_update' | 'location_unavailable', data: { lat, lng, timestamp } | null } — client must handle both event types",
        "coupling_type": "loose — event-driven push, client reconnects on drop"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "Courier device pings Location Ingestion Service every 5-15 seconds → Ingestion validates and writes to Redis (SET with 30s TTL) AND publishes to Redis Pub/Sub channel → Asynchronously, ingestion buffers writes to PostgreSQL for history → Location Push Gateway subscribes to Pub/Sub, receives updates, and forwards to connected customer WebSocket clients → If Redis key expires (no ping in 30s), GET returns nil, Gateway sends 'location_unavailable' to customer → Staleness Enforcement Middleware provides defense-in-depth timestamp validation on all read paths.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation)",
        "rationale": "Write path (ingestion → Redis + PostgreSQL) is completely separate from read path (Redis → Push Gateway → customer). This allows independent scaling and optimization of each path. The read model (Redis) is optimized for the 30-second freshness constraint. The write model (PostgreSQL) is optimized for durable append-only history."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "TTL-Based Staleness Enforcement",
        "rationale": "Redis TTL makes the 30-second domain rule structurally unbreakable at the infrastructure layer. When a key expires, it ceases to exist — there is no code path that can accidentally serve stale data from this store. This is far stronger than an application-layer WHERE timestamp > NOW() - 30s check."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Event-Driven Push (Pub/Sub + WebSocket)",
        "rationale": "Polling PostgreSQL every few seconds for N customers tracking M couriers creates O(N×M) query load and adds latency. Pub/Sub push inverts this: updates flow to interested clients with sub-second latency and constant cost per update regardless of observer count."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Defense-in-Depth for Domain Invariants",
        "rationale": "The 30-second staleness rule is Bird's hardest constraint. It is enforced at THREE layers: (1) Redis TTL auto-expires data, (2) Push Gateway sends 'unavailable' if no update in 30s, (3) Staleness Enforcement Middleware validates timestamp on reads. Any single layer failing still preserves the invariant."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Async Write-Behind to PostgreSQL",
        "rationale": "Historical writes to PostgreSQL are buffered and async. This keeps the critical ingestion path fast (Redis write only) and makes PostgreSQL failures non-blocking for real-time operations."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Live Tracking",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": [
          "CourierLocation (ephemeral — courier_id is the identity, latest GPS fix is the state, 30-second TTL is the lifecycle rule)",
          "TrackingSession (customer subscribing to a courier's location for a specific delivery)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Location History",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": [
          "LocationTrace (append-only sequence of GPS fixes for a courier over time, used for analytics and audit)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": [
          "Delivery (upstream context — provides the courier-customer-order mapping that determines who can track whom)"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery",
        "downstream": "Live Tracking",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Delivery context tells Live Tracking which courier is assigned to which delivery, enabling authorization of tracking sessions. Live Tracking conforms to Delivery's courier/order IDs."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Live Tracking",
        "downstream": "Location History",
        "relationship": "Published Language — Live Tracking emits location events that Location History consumes and persists. History has no influence on the real-time model."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Introduce Redis as a second data store instead of PostgreSQL-only",
      "gains": "Structural enforcement of 30-second staleness via TTL (impossible to serve expired data). Sub-millisecond reads. Native Pub/Sub for push. Purpose-built for ephemeral high-frequency data.",
      "sacrifices": "Added operational complexity — team must now manage Redis in addition to PostgreSQL. New failure mode (Redis outage = no live tracking). Team needs Redis expertise.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "PostgreSQL-only with application-layer staleness checks: Simpler ops but fragile enforcement. Every query must include WHERE received_at > NOW() - INTERVAL '30 seconds'. A single missed filter serves stale data. High write churn causes MVCC bloat requiring aggressive vacuuming. No native push mechanism — forced into polling.",
        "PostgreSQL with LISTEN/NOTIFY: Gets push semantics but LISTEN/NOTIFY is not designed for high-throughput fan-out. Limited to one database connection per listener. Does not solve the TTL/staleness enforcement problem."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "WebSocket push instead of client polling",
      "gains": "Sub-second update delivery. Eliminates O(N×M) polling load on datastore. Enables the 'location_unavailable' event when staleness occurs — customers see explicit feedback rather than a frozen pin.",
      "sacrifices": "Stateful connections at the edge. Requires sticky sessions or a connection registry. More complex client implementation.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Short polling every 5 seconds: Simpler but wastes resources, adds 0-5s latency on top of pipeline latency, and makes staleness feedback to customers delayed.",
        "Server-Sent Events (SSE): Viable alternative with simpler protocol. One-directional only but sufficient for this use case. Good fallback if WebSocket infrastructure is too complex initially."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Async write-behind to PostgreSQL (not synchronous dual-write)",
      "gains": "Ingestion latency stays low (Redis write only in critical path). PostgreSQL failures don't block live tracking. Batch inserts to PostgreSQL are more efficient.",
      "sacrifices": "Small window of potential history data loss if the buffer crashes before flushing. History may lag real-time by seconds.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Synchronous dual-write: Guarantees history consistency but doubles write latency and makes PostgreSQL a single point of failure for the entire system.",
        "Change Data Capture from Redis: Elegant but adds infrastructure complexity (Redis Streams + consumer)."
      ]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Current Location Store technology",
      "evolution_path": "Redis can be swapped for any TTL-capable KV store (Memcached, DynamoDB with TTL, etc.) without changing the read or write interfaces. The contract is SET-with-TTL and Pub/Sub — not Redis-specific."
    },
    {
      "area": "Push protocol",
      "evolution_path": "Can start with SSE (simpler) and migrate to WebSocket when bidirectional communication is needed. The Push Gateway abstracts this from the rest of the system."
    },
    {
      "area": "Location History storage",
      "evolution_path": "PostgreSQL works initially. If write volume becomes extreme, can migrate to TimescaleDB (PostgreSQL extension — minimal change) or a dedicated time-series database. The async write-behind buffer makes this swap transparent."
    },
    {
      "area": "Ping frequency and staleness window",
      "evolution_path": "The 30-second TTL and 5-15 second ping interval are configuration values, not hardcoded. Can be adjusted per-courier-tier or per-market without code changes."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "30-second staleness enforcement at infrastructure layer",
      "reason": "This is Bird's hardest domain invariant. The TTL-based enforcement in Redis is intentionally rigid — it must not be bypassed, weakened, or made configurable by application code. Defense-in-depth layers are non-negotiable."
    },
    {
      "area": "Separation of current-location reads from PostgreSQL",
      "reason": "Customer-facing current location MUST read from the TTL-protected store, never directly from PostgreSQL. PostgreSQL has no TTL — reading from it would violate the staleness invariant. This boundary is structural and must be enforced via code review and architectural fitness functions."
    },
    {
      "area": "Explicit 'location_unavailable' event",
      "reason": "Bird's rule says stale data 'must not be displayed.' This means absence of fresh data must be an EXPLICIT state communicated to the customer, not a silent freeze of the last known position. The Push Gateway must actively send unavailability — this is non-negotiable."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Redis failure causes complete loss of live tracking capability",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Redis Sentinel or Redis Cluster for HA. Graceful degradation: if Redis is down, Push Gateway sends 'location temporarily unavailable' to all customers rather than serving stale data or crashing. Never fall back to serving from PostgreSQL — that would violate the staleness invariant."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Clock skew between courier devices and servers causes incorrect staleness calculations",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Use server-received timestamp (received_at) as the authoritative time for TTL and staleness, NOT the device-reported timestamp. Device timestamp is stored for diagnostics only. Redis TTL is set on write — it counts from server time, avoiding device clock issues."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Network partitions cause courier pings to arrive late, triggering false staleness",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "This is correct behavior per Bird's rule — if the server hasn't received a location in 30 seconds, the data IS stale regardless of cause. The customer sees 'location unavailable' which is accurate. No mitigation needed — this is the system working as designed."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team unfamiliarity with Redis increases delivery time and operational risk",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Start with managed Redis (AWS ElastiCache, GCP Memorystore) to minimize ops burden. Redis usage is simple (SET/GET/PUBLISH/SUBSCRIBE with TTL) — not using complex data structures. Provide runbook for common failure modes."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Developers accidentally bypass the TTL-protected read path and query PostgreSQL for current location",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Enforce via architectural fitness tests: any query to courier_locations table with a freshness filter in customer-facing code triggers a CI failure. Provide a LocationReadService that ONLY reads from Redis — make it the sole authorized interface for current location."
