    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "NEVER expose PostgreSQL courier_locations table to customer-facing read paths — it has no TTL protection and will serve stale data",
      "NEVER use the device-reported timestamp for staleness decisions — use server-received time only",
      "NEVER cache location data in application memory without its own TTL — this creates a stale-data bypass around Redis TTL",
      "NEVER fall back to PostgreSQL reads when Redis is unavailable — show 'location unavailable' instead, preserving the domain invariant",
      "NEVER set Redis TTL higher than 30 seconds for production courier location keys — this directly violates Bird's domain rule",
      "AVOID synchronous dual-writes to Redis and PostgreSQL in the same request — PostgreSQL latency will dominate and slow ingestion"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [
    {
      "type": "domain_architecture_conflict",
      "description": "Bird's 30-second staleness rule fundamentally conflicts with the team's proposal to use PostgreSQL as the sole storage layer for current courier locations. PostgreSQL has no native TTL/expiry mechanism. Enforcing staleness purely in application code (WHERE timestamp > NOW() - 30s) is fragile: a single missed filter, ORM misconfiguration, or direct query serves stale data to customers, violating the domain invariant. The rule's absolute language ('must not be displayed') demands structural enforcement, not just procedural compliance.",
      "options": [
        "Option A: PostgreSQL-only with application-layer staleness checks. Simpler infrastructure. Risk: every read query must include the freshness filter — a single miss violates the invariant. No structural guarantee. High write churn causes MVCC bloat.",
        "Option B: Redis for current location (TTL-enforced) + PostgreSQL for history. Adds infrastructure but makes the 30-second rule structurally unbreakable. Natural fit for ephemeral high-frequency data. Native Pub/Sub enables push.",
        "Option C: PostgreSQL with a background job that deletes rows older than 30 seconds. Approximates TTL but has race conditions (data exists between job runs), adds GC pressure, and is semantically wrong — deletion destroys historical data."
      ],
      "recommendation": "Option B. Bird's rule uses the word 'must not' — this is a hard invariant, not a best-effort goal. Hard invariants deserve structural enforcement. Redis TTL provides exactly this. The added operational cost is justified by the certainty it provides. Start with managed Redis to minimize ops burden."
    }
  ],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 52,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "CQRS split between ephemeral current-location and historical location data is architecturally sound",
      "Redis TTL is the correct mechanism for structural staleness enforcement",
      "Push-based delivery (WebSocket/SSE) is clearly better than polling for real-time tracking",
      "Defense-in-depth for the staleness invariant is appropriate given Bird's absolute language"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Team's Redis operational readiness and willingness to adopt a second data store — could be a significant organizational blocker",
      "Exact scale requirements unknown — number of concurrent couriers, customers, and ping frequency affect whether Redis single-instance suffices or requires clustering",
      "Whether the 30-second rule applies uniformly or varies by context (e.g., is stale data acceptable for internal ops dashboards but not customer-facing?)",
      "Integration points with the Delivery context — how courier-to-order assignment is communicated is undefined"
